      <TR>
        <TD bgcolor='dimgray' valign='top' nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>Warblek</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='dimgray' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>I've done PLing with both a druid and a necro and necros are so horible compared to druids it shouldn't even be called PLing.  More like Slightly-Assisted leveling.</P><P>The fear kite method will make you break a sweat jumping back and forth between comps.  Fear breaks so randomly and snare wears off so fast you'll spend more time on the necro side than your warrior side.</P><P>One method I found slightly slower yet less labor intensive is to work blues instead of even/red cons.  Have the warrior get them to half then the necro roots and sends in pet.  The warr backs off, sits and the nec heals the warr, BoDs the mob and sits.  The warr should stay >50+hp and the nec will be fm by the next round.  Added benefit of doing it this way is your defense skill won't be 'newbie' still when you decide to start grouping.</P><P>Good places:<BR>Same places you'd group but your melee will be soloing non-stop instead so much faster exp.</P><P>-Loio for a long time (26ish)<BR>-Paw is great around 28-33 this way, super exp bonus.  Just go someplace quiet past the double doors so you don't hog spawns from real groups.</P><P>Past 32-33 it gets too tough to PL as a nec.  You're better off grouping in OT.</P><P> </font></td>
      </tr>
      <TR>
        <TD bgcolor='dimgray' valign='top' nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>Xandriana</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='dimgray' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>Fyi (and imo):<BR>You can pl with a necro long after the mid 30's.  In fact, I would say that pl'ing with a necro is better at the higher levels because it is at the higher levels that even a slowed blue mob can cause serious problems for a melee type.  Using fear kiting to pl becomes more advantageous at that point, not less.  <BR>Also, if you go by the method I explained above, you can pl just a tad less efficiently than a druid or shaman as long as you don't have to heal.<BR>Having to heal is what slows a necro down in pl'ing.  Avoid a situation where the necro has to heal and you will have better luck.</P><P>Added this in: to avoid the hassle of jumping from computer to computer, have all your commands hotkeyed on the same hot key page.  To stand, re-apply fear, and sit, I hit 9,0,9.  To send my pet I hit 1.  You don't even have to look at the keyboard or screen the necro is playing on. </P><P>As far as locations, you should already know them.  You know those spots you fear-kited at while solo'ing your necro?  Go back to them when the warrior is at the same level as you were then.</P><P><BR>Xandriana Xuileb`Xukuth<BR>Level 54 Teir`Dal Necromancer<BR>Tunare (Krieger)<BR>Wake up...wake up...time to die!</P><P>Edited by - Xandriana on 03/13/2001  17:22:22</font></td>
